"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 21–22
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-21-22.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (pre-existing: 21:1, 21:12, 22:15)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch21: triumphal entry cites Zech 9:9 explicitly; temple cleansing in the Court of the Gentiles
  draws on Isa 56:7 + Jer 7:11 (the Temple Sermon); fig tree as enacted prophetic sign of
  unfruitful Israel (Jer 8:13; Hos 9:10; Joel 1:7); wicked tenants parable anchored in Isa 5:1-7
  with Ps 118:22 as capstone
- Ch22: Tiberius denarius inscription "Divi Augusti Filius"; Sadducees restricted to Pentateuch,
  hence levirate marriage (Deut 25:5-10) as their test-case; Ps 110:1 is the most-cited OT verse
  in the NT — Jesus uses it to show the Messiah exceeds Davidic descent
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "21": {
    "2": '<p>The village of Bethphage ("house of unripe figs") stood near Bethany on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, approximately two miles from Jerusalem. Jesus sends two disciples ahead to collect a donkey and her colt — a prior arrangement is implied. The use of an animal that has "never been ridden" (<em>polon dedemenon</em>) echoes the requirement of unused animals for sacred purposes in the OT (Num 19:2; Deut 21:3; 1 Sam 6:7); a beast not yet broken for ordinary use was considered ritually appropriate for sacred or royal use.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"The Lord has need of them" (<em>ho kyrios autōn chreian echei</em>) — the use of <em>kyrios</em> (Lord) may function both as a polite title and as a coded authorization for disciples who had made prior arrangements. The phrase "immediately he will send them" suggests the owner is known to Jesus, reinforcing the reading of a deliberate pre-arranged signal rather than a miraculous prediction.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The explicit fulfillment formula "this took place to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet" frames the entire entry as enacted prophecy. Matthew\'s two-animal reading of Zech 9:9 (both the donkey and her colt) follows a literal reading of the Hebrew parallelism in which the second animal (colt) is the same beast described by synonymous parallel. Most commentators understand only one animal was ridden; Matthew emphasizes both as fulfilling the Zechariah text precisely.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The citation of Zech 9:9 ("See, your king comes to you, gentle and riding on a donkey, and on a colt, the foal of a donkey") deliberately sets a donkey-riding king against the expected war-horse king. In the ancient world, riding a horse was the posture of conquest; a donkey was the mount of a king coming in peace (1 Kgs 1:33, where Solomon rides David\'s mule at his coronation). "Gentle" (<em>praus</em>) is the same word from the Beatitude of 5:5 ("blessed are the meek"); the Messiah\'s arrival style is already an enacted hermeneutic of the kingdom.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The disciples carry out the instruction exactly as given — a Matthean emphasis on obedience to Jesus\' word. The straightforward execution underlines the theological point: what happens next is intentional, scripted from the prophetic tradition, and performed in full awareness of its symbolic weight.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Placing garments on the animals and then on them — the disciples lay their own cloaks on the animals and spread more cloaks for Jesus to ride upon. The placing of garments under a king echoes Jehu\'s anointing in 2 Kgs 9:13, where the captains spread their garments on the steps for Jehu. The gesture is a spontaneous royal coronation rite, performed by those who recognize Jesus as king.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The crowd spreads garments on the road — the same royal gesture from 2 Kgs 9:13, now performed by a much larger group. The cutting of branches from the trees: in Mark and John the branches are identified as palm branches (<em>baion phoinikōn</em>). Palm branches were a Jewish symbol of national victory and messianic hope (1 Macc 13:51; 2 Macc 10:7), used in the Feast of Tabernacles (<em>lulab</em>). The combination of garments and branches is a full-scale royal welcome procession.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Hosanna to the Son of David" — <em>hōsanna</em> is a Greek transliteration of the Hebrew <em>hoshia na</em> ("save now") from Ps 118:25, a Hallel psalm sung during Passover and Tabernacles. What began as a petition for divine rescue had become a liturgical acclamation; by the first century it functioned more as a shout of praise than a petition. The phrase "Blessed is he who comes in the name of the Lord" is Ps 118:26, the standard pilgrim greeting for those arriving in Jerusalem for festivals. Combining this with "Son of David" transforms it into a messianic acclaim.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Who is this?" — the question from the Jerusalem crowd distinguishes them from the Galilean pilgrims who knew Jesus. Jerusalem residents would have been far less familiar with him. The city is described as being "stirred" (<em>eseisthē</em> — shaken, moved) — the same verb root as <em>seismos</em> (earthquake), used in Matthew for cosmic disruption (27:51; 28:2). The city\'s agitation echoes Herod\'s agitation at the Magi\'s arrival (2:3), framing the entry as a moment of messianic crisis.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"This is the prophet Jesus, from Nazareth of Galilee" — the pilgrims\' identification of Jesus as "the prophet" positions him in the prophetic tradition (Deut 18:15, the promised prophet like Moses), stopping short of the fuller messianic title. Nazareth ("from Galilee") was an unexpected origin for the Messiah (John 7:41-52), highlighting the social and geographic reversal embedded in Jesus\' ministry from the start.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"It is written, \'My house shall be called a house of prayer\' (Isa 56:7), but you are making it a den of robbers" (Jer 7:11). The Isaiah citation is deliberately partial — Isaiah 56:7 reads "a house of prayer for all peoples," and the omission of "for all peoples" highlights what was being prevented: Gentile prayer in the only court open to them. Jeremiah 7:11 comes from the Temple Sermon, in which Jeremiah indicts the temple as a refuge for those who continue sinning, creating the same irony Jesus invokes.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"The blind and the lame came to him in the temple, and he healed them" — this is historically significant because the Levitical law excluded the blind and lame from priestly service (Lev 21:17-23). The Qumran community also excluded the physically disabled from their assembly (1QSa 2:5-7). Jesus\' healing of these persons in the temple precincts is a direct enacted challenge to the purity logic that excluded them, reclaiming the temple as a space of divine restoration rather than ritual exclusion.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The chief priests and scribes are "indignant" (<em>ēganaktēsan</em>) at the healing and the children\'s hosannas. Their hostility is both to Jesus\' authority and to the messianic acclamation — if acknowledged, it would demand a response that would either alienate Rome (if the messiah were a political threat) or undermine their authority (if legitimate). The children\'s cry forces them to take a public position.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Do you hear what these are saying?" — the chief priests\' challenge prompts Jesus to cite Ps 8:2 (LXX: "Out of the mouths of infants and nursing babies you have prepared praise"). The LXX translates the Hebrew "you have established strength" as "you have prepared praise" — Matthew uses the LXX text precisely because it names the praise of the vulnerable as a divine appointment, not an embarrassment. The citation turns the complaint into an affirmation: the children\'s hosannas fulfill scripture.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Bethany was a village on the eastern slope of the Mount of Olives, approximately two miles from Jerusalem. It served as Jesus\' regular lodging during Passion Week — close enough to walk to the temple daily (as the Jerusalem crowd pressed too many thousands for easy accommodations) but outside the city walls. The village was the home of Mary, Martha, and Lazarus (John 11-12).</p>',
    "18": '<p>"As he was returning to the city in the morning" — traveling from Bethany to Jerusalem in the early morning was standard for pilgrims; the day\'s temple activities began at dawn. Jesus is "hungry" (<em>epeinase</em>) — a detail of human physicality that grounds the fig tree episode in normal experience before its symbolic dimension becomes apparent.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The fig tree in full leaf but with no fruit — in Palestine, fig trees develop their edible early figs (<em>paggim</em>, green knobs that appear with the leaves in spring) before the main crop; a tree in leaf might reasonably be expected to have at least these early figs. The immediate withering upon the curse is the enacted sign. The OT consistently uses the fig tree as an image of Israel: its fruitfulness represents covenant faithfulness (Jer 8:13; Hos 9:10; Joel 1:7; Mic 7:1); its withering, covenant judgment. The episode brackets the temple action (vv. 12-13 // vv. 20-22), creating a commentary relationship.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The disciples\' astonishment — "How did the fig tree wither at once?" — focuses on the immediacy of the sign rather than its significance. In Mark\'s account the withering is noticed the next morning, creating a two-day structure that more explicitly brackets the temple action. Matthew\'s compression makes the enacted judgment and the lesson about faith a single unified incident.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"If you have faith and do not doubt, you will not only do what was done to the fig tree, but even if you say to this mountain, \'Be taken up and thrown into the sea,\' it will happen" — moving mountains was a hyperbolic rabbinic expression for doing something extraordinarily difficult (b. Berakhot 63b: "uprooting mountains" as a title for a great teacher). The "mountain" may also allude specifically to the Temple Mount (Zion), given the immediate context of temple judgment. The faith-language redirects from the sign\'s symbolism to the disciples\' own dependence on God.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"Whatever you ask in prayer, you will receive, if you have faith" — the promise is not a blank check but is embedded in the context of prayer offered in the confidence that comes from knowing God\'s will. The connection between the fig tree cursing and the promise of prayer clarifies that the disciples\'  authority is derivative and dependent — not self-generated but received through relationship with the Father.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"By what authority are you doing these things?" (<em>en poia exousia tauta poieis</em>) — the chief priests and elders challenge Jesus in the temple precincts, the natural venue for questions of religious authority. The question targets both the temple action (driving out the sellers) and the ongoing teaching. In the Jewish system, authority derived from ordination in a chain of transmission: a rabbi taught with the authority of his teacher, who transmitted from his teacher, back to Moses (m. Avot 1:1). Jesus lacked any recognized rabbinic ordination.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Jesus\' counter-question about John\'s baptism is a political masterstroke. "The baptism of John, from where did it come? From heaven or from man?" — this question puts the religious leaders in an impossible position. If they say "from heaven," Jesus will ask why they did not believe John (and by implication, why they reject Jesus, whom John endorsed). If they say "from man," they risk the crowd, who "all hold John to be a prophet." The dilemma is not rhetorical evasion but a genuine epistemological point: both John and Jesus derive authority from the same divine source.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The deliberation among the religious leaders — "If we say \'From heaven,\' he will say to us, \'Why then did you not believe him?\'" — reveals that their question about authority was not a genuine inquiry but a political maneuver. Their inability to answer exposes their criterion: they assess authority by whether it serves their institutional interests, not by whether it comes from God. This self-exposure is itself the answer to their question about Jesus\' authority.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"But if we say \'From man,\' we are afraid of the crowd, for they all hold John to be a prophet" — the leaders\' fear of the crowd is a recurring theme in the passion narrative (21:46; 26:5). Their authority is derived from popular recognition, which makes them vulnerable to popular repudiation. The crowd\'s view of John limits their options — they cannot safely deny prophetic authority in general without undercutting their own position.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"We do not know" — a public admission of ignorance or unwillingness to commit. Jesus declines to answer their original question on the grounds that they will not engage honestly: "Neither will I tell you by what authority I do these things." The exchange does not end in a draw; it demonstrates that the leaders have forfeited the right to evaluate Jesus\' authority by refusing to engage the evidence they already have (John\'s ministry).</p>',
    "28": '<p>The parable of the two sons opens a sequence of three parables (two sons, wicked tenants, wedding banquet) all aimed at the chief priests and Pharisees. "A man had two sons" — the form is a familiar rabbinic mashal. The first son refuses and then goes; the second agrees and does not go. The application in v.31 makes the identification explicit: the religious leaders are the second son — verbal compliance without action.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The first son says "I will not" (<em>ou thelō</em>) — a direct refusal, without even polite deferral. "Afterward he changed his mind and went" — <em>metamelomai</em> (regret, change of mind after the fact) is the same word used for Judas\'s regret in 27:3. The change is behavioral: he actually performs the work. In the kingdom economy, repentance expressed in action counts; verbal compliance without action does not.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The second son says "I go, sir" (<em>egō, kyrie</em>) — the respectful address and immediate verbal assent represent formal compliance with the father\'s instruction. "But he did not go" — the gap between the respectful answer and the actual performance is the parable\'s indictment. The religious leaders have spent their careers saying "I go, sir" to God while their actual conduct moved in the opposite direction.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Which of the two did the will of his father?" — the answer is inescapable: the first. "Truly I say to you, the tax collectors and the prostitutes go into the kingdom of God before you" — these groups represent the maximum social and religious stigma: tax collectors as collaborators with Rome and cheats; prostitutes as violators of sexual purity norms. Both responded to John\'s call to repentance in a way the religious leaders did not.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"For John came to you in the way of righteousness, and you did not believe him, but the tax collectors and the prostitutes believed him" — John\'s ministry is again the crux. The response to John is the test case for authentic kingdom orientation. The religious leaders saw the response of the socially disreputable and still did not repent or believe — their refusal was not ignorance but resistance to evidence.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The parable of the wicked tenants opens with "There was a master of a house who planted a vineyard" — an explicit echo of Isa 5:1-7, the Song of the Vineyard, where YHWH is the owner who plants Israel as his vineyard. Matthew\'s audience would have recognized the Isaianic frame immediately. The detailed vineyard infrastructure (fence, winepress, watchtower) corresponds to Isa 5:2 almost word for word, marking this as a deliberate midrashic reworking of Israel\'s foundational judgment narrative.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The landowner "sent his servants to the tenants to get his fruit" — servants sent to collect the owner\'s portion of the harvest are a standard feature of ancient agricultural tenancy arrangements. In the allegorical reading, the servants are the prophets sent by God to receive the covenant "fruit" (obedience, righteousness) from Israel. The phrase "when the season for fruit drew near" (<em>hote de ēggisen ho kairos tōn karpōn</em>) echoes the eschatological framing: the harvest of judgment approaches.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The tenants\' treatment of the first round of servants — beaten, killed, stoned — is an allegorical summary of the deuteronomistic prophet-killing tradition: the repeated rejection and murder of YHWH\'s prophets throughout Israel\'s history (2 Chr 36:15-16; Jer 7:25-26; Neh 9:26). This tradition was well-established in Second Temple Judaism; Jesus draws on it as a known interpretive framework for why Israel\'s leadership repeatedly rejected divine messengers.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Again he sent other servants, more than the first, and they did the same to them" — the escalation of servants and the repeated rejection follows the pattern of the prophetic corpus: the more urgently God sent messengers, the more violently they were received. The parable compresses centuries of prophetic history into a single repeated cycle to expose the structural pattern of Israel\'s leadership\'s response.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"Afterward he sent his son to them, saying, \'They will respect my son\'" — the son\'s sending is the climactic and final appeal. In the allegorical reading the son is Jesus; his arrival is qualitatively different from the servants\' (the prophets\'): he is the heir, not merely a messenger. The owner\'s logic — "they will respect my son" — is the logic of grace that sends after all rejection, not the logic of rational expectation.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"But when the tenants saw the son, they said to themselves, \'This is the heir. Come, let us kill him and have his inheritance\'" — the tenants\' reasoning reflects a real dynamic in ancient tenancy law: if the heir died without descendants, tenants who had continuous possession might gain ownership rights under certain legal frameworks. The detail grounds the parable in recognizable economic motivation rather than mere wickedness, making the indictment more precise: they murder for gain.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"They seized him and threw him out of the vineyard and killed him" — the sequence (seized, expelled, killed) mirrors the passion narrative (arrested, brought outside the city, crucified). Jerusalem was outside the city walls where crucifixions occurred; "thrown out of the vineyard" corresponds to the execution outside the city as an act of expulsion from covenant community.</p>',
    "40": '<p>The rhetorical question — "When therefore the owner of the vineyard comes, what will he do to those tenants?" — invites the listeners to pronounce their own judgment. This is the legal trap: the audience speaks its own verdict before realizing the parable is about them. The technique mirrors Nathan\'s parable to David (2 Sam 12:1-7), where David condemns himself before the application is made.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The chief priests and Pharisees answer their own question: "He will put those wretches to a miserable death and let out the vineyard to other tenants who will give him the fruits in their seasons." The phrase "give him the fruits in their seasons" (<em>apodōsousin autō tous karpous en tois kairois autōn</em>) echoes the covenant-faithfulness language of the Torah: bearing fruit is the sign of authentic covenant relationship. The "other tenants" who will receive the vineyard are identified in v.43 as "a nation producing its fruits."</p>',
    "42": '<p>"The stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone; this was the Lord\'s doing, and it is marvelous in our eyes" — a citation of Ps 118:22-23. Psalm 118 was the Passover Hallel psalm, sung in the temple during the festival; the rejected-stone image was available for messianic application. In 1 Pet 2:4-8 and Acts 4:11 the same psalm text is applied explicitly to the resurrected Christ. The paradox — the builders who should recognize good building material reject the key stone — mirrors the religious leaders who should recognize the Messiah.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"The kingdom of God will be taken away from you and given to a people producing its fruits" (<em>ethne poiounti tous karpous autēs</em>) — <em>ethnei</em> (nation/people) is singular, not plural "nations/Gentiles." This does not refer to the Gentile mission per se but to a renewed covenant community (which may include Gentiles) defined by fruit-bearing rather than ethnic heritage. The logic is Deuteronomy\'s covenant-transfer theology: the land goes to those who keep the covenant.</p>',
    "44": '<p>"And the one who falls on this stone will be broken to pieces; and when it falls on anyone, it will crush him" — a double judgment image combining Isa 8:14-15 (stumbling on the rock of offense) and Dan 2:44-45 (the stone that crushes the statue). The stone of Ps 118:22 is now the eschatological rock of judgment: those who stumble over it are broken; those on whom it falls are crushed. The rejected cornerstone becomes the stone of final reckoning.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"When the chief priests and the Pharisees heard his parables, they perceived that he was speaking about them" (<em>egnōsan hoti peri autōn legei</em>) — the moment of recognition confirms the legal trap has closed. The parables\' transparency is their function: the leaders\' self-identification is the beginning of their self-condemnation. Their recognition, however, does not produce repentance but accelerates their plot to eliminate him.</p>',
    "46": '<p>"And although they were seeking to arrest him, they feared the crowds, because they held him to be a prophet" — the fear of the crowd is the repeated constraint on the leaders\' plans throughout the passion narrative. The popular perception of Jesus as a prophet (cf. v.11) provides protective cover in the public arena; the leaders must find a way to act against Jesus away from the festival crowds. This dynamic drives the plot toward Judas\'s offer to facilitate a private arrest (26:14-16).</p>'
  },
  "22": {
    "1": '<p>The parable of the wedding banquet continues the three-parable sequence (two sons, wicked tenants, wedding banquet) addressed to the chief priests and Pharisees. The kingdom-of-heaven comparison to a royal wedding feast draws on widespread ancient imagery: banquets as eschatological celebration (Isa 25:6-8; 1 Enoch 62:14), the marriage of YHWH with Israel as covenant metaphor (Hos 2:19-20), and the messianic feast as the climactic event of the new age.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A king who gives a wedding banquet for his son — the royal wedding is the highest social occasion, obligating the greatest honor response from those invited. In the ancient patron-client world, a royal invitation was effectively a command; refusal was a calculated political insult, implying that the guest recognized neither the king\'s superiority nor his own dependence on royal favor.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The first round of servants sent to call those who had been invited: the "called" (<em>keklēmenous</em>) represent those who had received advance notice — in Jewish application, Israel, the covenant people who had been long prepared for the messianic invitation. "But they would not come" — the refusal without stated reason emphasizes its arbitrariness and insult. No polite excuse is offered; they simply do not come.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Tell those who are invited: See, I have prepared my dinner, my oxen and my fat calves have been slaughtered, and everything is ready" — the enumeration of prepared food (fatted animals already slaughtered) signals that the banquet cannot simply be postponed. The feast is ready; the only question is whether the guests will come. The urgency and prepared state of the meal heighten the insult of the ongoing refusal.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"But they paid no attention and went off, one to his farm, another to his business" — the guests\' distraction is ordinary business: farm and trade, the normal economy of daily life. Their refusal is not malicious but indifferent — the king\'s feast is simply less important than their regular commercial concerns. This indifference is itself the insult: the kingdom\'s invitation is met not with hostility but with a shrug.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"While the rest seized his servants, treated them shamefully, and killed them" — the violent wing of the refusal escalates beyond indifference to active persecution. In the allegorical reading this refers to the prophets\' treatment; in the narrative\'s logic it triggers the king\'s military response. The combination of commercial indifference (v.5) and active violence (v.6) represents the full spectrum of Israel\'s rejection of God\'s messengers.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"The king was angry, and he sent his troops and destroyed those murderers and burned their city" — this verse has been read from very early in Christian interpretation as a reference to the Roman destruction of Jerusalem in 70 CE. If Matthew was written after 70 CE (or even in knowledge of escalating Roman-Jewish tensions leading to it), the burned city would be unmistakably transparent. Whether pre- or post-70, the destruction is the covenantal judgment of a covenant people who murdered the king\'s representatives.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"The wedding is ready, but those invited were not worthy" (<em>axios</em>) — worthiness here is not a moral qualification but a relational one: they were unworthy in the sense that they refused the relationship the invitation embodied. The feast proceeds without them; the host\'s generosity is not limited by the invited guests\' refusal. The kingdom will find its recipients.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Go therefore to the main roads and invite to the wedding feast as many as you find" — the roads (<em>diexodous tōn hodōn</em>, literally "exits of the roads," crossroads or major junctions) are where those who have no place in the social network congregate: travelers, the displaced, the marginal. The geographic move from private invitation list to open road is the social move from covenant insiders to all who will come.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Those servants went out into the roads and gathered all whom they found, both bad and good" (<em>ponērous te kai agathous</em>) — the lack of screening is the point. The kingdom community is a mixed gathering; sorting occurs at the end, not the beginning. This detail prepares for the wedding garment episode (v.11-14): the open invitation does not eliminate the expectation of transformation, but that transformation is not a pre-condition for entry.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"But when the king came in to look at the guests, he saw there a man who had no wedding garment" — the wedding garment (<em>enduma gamou</em>) is not a specific identifiable item of clothing but represents transformed readiness for the feast. It may reflect the practice of wealthy hosts providing robes to guests (cf. Esth 6:8; 8:15) — in which case the man has refused what was provided. More likely it is a metaphorical garment of righteousness (Isa 61:10; Rev 19:8), representing the moral transformation that true reception of the kingdom invitation produces.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Friend, how did you get in here without a wedding garment?" — <em>hetaire</em> (friend), the same formal address Jesus uses to Judas at the betrayal (26:50) and to the grumbling vineyard worker (20:13): cordial but ominous, signaling a relationship that has gone badly wrong. "He was speechless" (<em>ho de ephistato</em>) — literally, "he was muzzled." No defense is possible. Entry without transformation is exposed as what it is.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Bind him hand and foot and cast him into the outer darkness" — the binding of hands and feet immobilizes: this is not mere expulsion but a removal that forecloses all movement. "Outer darkness" (<em>to skotos to exōteron</em>) with "weeping and gnashing of teeth" is Matthew\'s recurring eschatological judgment formula (8:12; 13:42, 50; 24:51; 25:30), describing the condition of those outside the kingdom feast. The severity of the judgment for the ungarmented guest underscores the seriousness of receiving the invitation without the transformation it calls for.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"For many are called, but few are chosen" (<em>polloi gar eisin klētoi, oligoi de eklektoi</em>) — the distinction between the called (<em>klētoi</em>) and the chosen (<em>eklektoi</em>) is not a predestination formula but an observation about response. The initial invitation is wide (all on the roads); the "chosen" are those who both enter and are clothed appropriately — those who respond to the invitation in a manner that fits what the banquet requires.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The Pharisees send their disciples together with the Herodians — an unusual alliance, since Herodians were supporters of Herod Antipas and the Roman client-king system, while Pharisees were generally resistant to Hellenistic accommodation. They share a common adversary. The flattering introduction — "Teacher, we know that you are true and teach the way of God truthfully, and you do not care about anyone\'s opinion" — is precisely the setup for a question designed to force a politically fatal answer.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Is it lawful to pay taxes to Caesar, or not?" — the Greek <em>kēnsos</em> (Latin <em>census</em>) is the direct tribute paid to Rome, not merely commercial tariffs. This was the most politically charged fiscal question in first-century Judea. A "yes" answer would alienate Jewish nationalists who viewed the tribute as an acknowledgment of Rome\'s sovereignty over the holy land (which belonged to YHWH alone). A "no" answer would constitute sedition against Rome and invite immediate arrest.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"But Jesus, aware of their malice (<em>ponērian</em>), said, \'Why put me to the test, you hypocrites?\'" — the word <em>ponēria</em> (malice, wickedness) is pointed: not merely tactical cunning but moral corruption. The accusation of hypocrisy is appropriate because their framing as truth-seekers (v.16) directly contradicts their actual intent. The exposure of the test itself is part of the response.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"Show me the coin for the tax" — the denarius (<em>dēnarion</em>) used for the imperial tribute was a Roman silver coin. The standard tribute coin of Tiberius\'s reign (14-37 CE) bore on the obverse his image and the inscription <em>TI CAESAR DIVI AVG F AVGVSTVS</em> ("Tiberius Caesar Augustus, son of the divine Augustus") and on the reverse the seated figure of Livia (or Pax) with the inscription <em>PONTIF MAXIM</em> ("Pontifex Maximus," high priest). The coin was a walking assertion of Roman imperial theology — Caesar as son of a god and supreme priest.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Whose likeness and inscription is this?" (<em>tinos hē eikōn hautē kai hē epigraphē</em>) — the word <em>eikōn</em> (image) carries weight beyond mere identification. Genesis 1:26-27 states that humans are made in the <em>image</em> (<em>tselem</em>/LXX <em>eikōn</em>) of God. The question about whose image is on the coin sets up the counter-question: whose image is on the human person? The coin belongs to Caesar because it bears his image; the human person belongs to God because it bears God\'s image.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Render therefore to Caesar the things that are Caesar\'s, and to God the things that are God\'s" — the answer is not a two-kingdom political theology dividing secular and sacred spheres. It is a subversive limitation of Caesar\'s domain: give Caesar back his coin, which bears his image; but give to God everything that bears God\'s image — which is the human person, all human life and loyalty. The practical concession (pay the tax) is nested within a theological claim that limits Caesar\'s sovereignty absolutely.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"They marveled, and they left him and went away" — the question is dissolved rather than answered on its own terms. Jesus refuses the either-or and reframes the question around the image-of-God theology, leaving both collaborationist and nationalist positions unsatisfied while affirming a higher sovereignty. The astonishment is at the rhetorical and theological skill of the escape, which also silences further pursuit of this line of attack.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"The same day Sadducees came to him" — the Sadducees were the priestly aristocracy who controlled the temple and collaborated with Roman administration. Unlike the Pharisees, they accepted only the written Torah (rejecting oral tradition), and denied resurrection, angels, and spirits (Acts 23:8; Josephus, <em>Ant.</em> 18.1.4). Their rejection of resurrection was not skepticism but a principled Pentateuchal exegesis: Moses\' Torah said nothing explicit about it. The resurrection question is therefore not a theological curiosity but a direct challenge to Jesus\' teaching on Jesus\' own hermeneutical grounds.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The levirate marriage law (Deut 25:5-10) required a man to marry his deceased brother\'s wife if the brother died childless, to "raise up offspring for his brother" and preserve the family name and property. The practice is documented in Gen 38 (Judah and Tamar) and the book of Ruth. The Sadducees construct a reductio ad absurdum: seven brothers, one wife, no children — whose wife is she in the resurrection? The test-case is designed to expose the resurrection doctrine as logically incoherent within Torah categories.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The first brother dies — the conditional structure ("if the first dies") repeats with mechanical regularity through seven brothers. The fictional construct is deliberate: a real case is unnecessary; the logical problem is what matters. The repetition reinforces the absurdity of the scenario and the apparently insoluble nature of the question within resurrection theology as the Sadducees understand it.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The second brother and the third, through all seven — the escalating numbers serve the rhetorical purpose of the <em>reductio</em>: the more brothers, the more impossible resurrection becomes within the Sadducean framing of it as a simple resumption of earthly conditions. Each iteration tightens the logical trap they are trying to set.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"Last of all, the woman died" — the woman outlives all seven husbands, making the puzzle symmetrically unresolvable. In terms of levirate law, her final death closes all claims. The Sadducees\' question "whose wife will she be of the seven?" presupposes that resurrection means resumption of earthly social and legal relationships — precisely the assumption Jesus will challenge.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"In the resurrection, therefore, of the seven, whose wife will she be? For they all had her" — the word "had" (<em>eschon</em>) is the same term used for marriage possession throughout the pericope. The question is framed entirely within the legal categories of marital ownership and obligation. Jesus\' answer will reframe resurrection life as categorically different from the conditions that make the question arise.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"You are wrong, because you know neither the Scriptures nor the power of God" — a pointed double indictment: hermeneutical failure (not knowing scripture) and theological failure (not knowing God\'s power). The order is significant — misreading scripture leads to underestimating God. The Sadducees\' Pentateuchal exegesis is both their strongest suit and, in Jesus\' view, where they most fail.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"In the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels in heaven" — Jesus\'s first move rejects the Sadducees\' premise: resurrection does not restore earthly legal and social structures. The resurrected state is qualitatively new, analogous to the existence of angels (spiritual beings who neither marry nor are defined by kinship). The levirate scenario becomes inapplicable because the institution it regulates does not exist in that state.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"And as for the resurrection of the dead, have you not read what was said to you by God?" — the second move addresses the resurrection question directly from the Pentateuch, the only scripture the Sadducees acknowledged as authoritative. "Said to you by God" — not "written" but "said," emphasizing the living, present speech of God, which will be relevant to the argument.</p>',
    "32": '<p>"\'I am the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob\'" (Exod 3:6, the burning bush) — Jesus\'s exegetical argument: God says "I am" (present tense) the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. If these patriarchs were simply dead and gone, there would be no living relationship for God to claim. "He is not God of the dead, but of the living" — the present tense of the divine identity statement implies ongoing relationship with the patriarchs, which requires their continued existence. This is exegesis of the Torah on its own terms, using the very text the Sadducees recognize.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"And when the crowd heard it, they were astonished at his teaching" — the crowd\'s astonishment signals that Jesus has given an answer that satisfies both exegetically (from the Pentateuch) and logically (the resurrection life question). The Sadducees are silenced not by rhetorical evasion but by a better exegesis of their own authoritative text. The crowd perceives the quality of the argument.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The Pharisees "gathered together" (<em>synēchthēsan epi to auto</em>) when they heard that Jesus had silenced the Sadducees — the phrase implies a council or deliberate assembly. The three controversy episodes (Caesar\'s coin, resurrection, the great commandment) represent a coordinated series of tests by the different factions of the Sanhedrin. After each, the questioners are silenced; after all three, Jesus takes the offensive with his own question (v.41-46).</p>',
    "35": '<p>"And one of them, a lawyer (<em>nomikos</em>), asked him a question to test him" — <em>nomikos</em> designates a specialist in Torah interpretation, equivalent to <em>grammateus</em> (scribe) elsewhere. The question is presented as a test (<em>peirazōn</em>), framing it as adversarial, though the parallel in Mark 12:28-34 presents the scribe as genuinely interested and ends with Jesus commending him. Matthew emphasizes the hostile context.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"Teacher, which is the great commandment in the Law?" — the rabbinic tradition debated which commandments were "heavy" (<em>chamurot</em>) and "light" (<em>qallot</em>), and how to identify the fundamental principle underlying the Torah\'s 613 commandments. Various teachers offered summaries: Hillel summarized Torah as the Golden Rule; R. Akiva named Lev 19:18 as the greatest principle; R. Simlai (b. Makkot 23b) counted 613 commandments and attributed various summaries to different prophets. The question was a standard rabbinic discussion, not unique to the Pharisees\' challenge to Jesus.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind" — the citation of Deut 6:5, the Shema (<em>shema</em> = "hear"), the central Jewish confession of God\'s unity and Israel\'s total devotion to him. The Shema was (and is) recited twice daily in Jewish practice, at morning and evening (m. Berakhot 1:1-2). "With all your mind" adds the intellectual faculty to the Hebrew text\'s heart-soul-strength triad, emphasizing that love of God engages every human capacity.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"This is the great and first commandment" — <em>megalē kai prōtē</em> (great and first). The superlative establishes priority, not merely sequence. All other commandments derive their weight from their relationship to this foundational orientation. The logic is: if one\'s entire person is oriented toward God, keeping specific commandments follows as natural expression of that orientation.</p>',
    "39": '<p>"And a second is like it: You shall love your neighbor as yourself" (Lev 19:18) — "like it" (<em>homoia autē</em>) means similar in character and weight, not merely secondary. The two commandments form a pair: love of God (vertical orientation) and love of neighbor (horizontal expression). Lev 19:18 in its context ("love your neighbor as yourself; I am YHWH") grounds neighbor-love in the nature of YHWH, making it an extension of the first commandment rather than an independent ethic.</p>',
    "40": '<p>"On these two commandments depend all the Law and the Prophets" (<em>kremantai holos ho nomos kai hoi prophētai</em>) — "hang" (<em>kremannymi</em>) is the technical term: all 613 commandments are suspended from these two as from a hook. The double love command is not a replacement for the Torah but its structural support. This summary was influential in early Christianity (Rom 13:9-10; Gal 5:14) as a principle for Gentile communities navigating Torah-observance.</p>',
    "41": '<p>Jesus takes the initiative while the Pharisees are still gathered: "What do you think about the Christ? Whose son is he?" — this is not a Christological declaration but a hermeneutical probe. The Pharisees\' answer — "the son of David" — is correct but incomplete. Jesus uses Ps 110:1 to show that the expected Davidic Messiah must be understood in a way that the standard "son of David" framework cannot contain.</p>',
    "42": '<p>"Whose son is he?" — the Pharisees answer with standard messianic expectation: "the son of David." This is consistent with the Scriptures (2 Sam 7:12-14; Ps 89:3-4; Isa 9:7; 11:1) and with what the crowds have been calling Jesus throughout Matthew (9:27; 12:23; 15:22; 20:30-31; 21:9). The answer is not wrong; it is inadequate to account for what Ps 110 says about the Messiah.</p>',
    "43": '<p>"He said to them, \'How is it then that David, in the Spirit, calls him Lord?\'" — "in the Spirit" (<em>en pneumati</em>) frames Ps 110 as prophetically inspired, not merely poetic. The argument requires that David is genuinely speaking about his own descendant and genuinely calling him "Lord" — both facts are necessary for the logical point. If David\'s descendant is merely a human king, why does David acknowledge him as superior?</p>',
    "44": '<p>The citation of Ps 110:1 ("The Lord said to my Lord: Sit at my right hand, until I put your enemies under your feet") — Ps 110:1 is the most frequently cited OT text in the NT (Matt 22:44; 26:64; Mark 12:36; 14:62; Luke 20:42; Acts 2:34-35; 1 Cor 15:25; Heb 1:13; 10:12-13). In the first century, Ps 110 was read as Davidic and messianic. The "Lord" whom David addresses ("my Lord") sits at the right hand of YHWH — a position of supreme divine favor (Ps 110:5 identifies this figure as a divine warrior). David\'s own son, in this reading, occupies a position that transcends Davidic kingship entirely.</p>',
    "45": '<p>"If then David calls him Lord, how is he his son?" — the logical dilemma: in the ancient honor-code, fathers do not call their sons "Lord" (the honor-flow is downward from father to son in the family hierarchy). If David calls his descendant "Lord," the descendant\'s status cannot be explained by his Davidic descent alone. Jesus does not supply the answer — he leaves the dilemma open, inviting recognition of what the title "Son of David" must mean if Ps 110:1 is also true of the Messiah.</p>',
    "46": '<p>"And no one was able to answer him a word, nor from that day did anyone dare to ask him any more questions" — the silence of all three factions (Herodians, Sadducees, Pharisees) after the three controversy dialogues and Jesus\' own question marks the end of public controversy. The authority question raised in 21:23 ("by what authority?") is answered implicitly: one who can silence all challengers from within their own traditions and from the most authoritative text of the Hebrew Bible is operating with an authority that surpasses the institutional sources they represent.</p>'
  }
}

